05803nam a22007695i 9780674275980DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742759807 a10.4159/97806742759802doi  a(DE-B1597)618850  a(OCoLC)1306463268  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a332.02852231 aLaboure, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocratizing Finance :bThe Radical Promise of Fintech /cNicolas Deffrennes, Marion Laboure. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Millennials—The Subprime Generation? -- t2. Banking in the Digital Era -- t3. The Emergence of Robo-Advisors -- t4. The Digitalization of Public Services -- t5. A Macroeconomic View of Growth, Inequality, and Financial Exclusion -- t6. Fintech, Financial Inclusion, and Economic Infrastructure -- t7. The Interplay of Fintech and Government -- t8. Toward a Cashless Society -- t9. Digital Currencies: The Ultimate Hard-Power Tool -- tConclusion -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are only in the early stages of a broader revolution that will impact every aspect of the global economy, including commerce and government services. Coming financial technology innovations could improve the quality of life for all people. Over the past few decades, digital technology has transformed finance. Financial technology (fintech) has enabled more people with fewer resources, in more places around the world, to take advantage of banking, insurance, credit, investment, and other financial services. Marion Laboure and Nicolas Deffrennes argue that these changes are only the tip of the iceberg. A much broader revolution is under way that, if steered correctly, will lead to huge and beneficial social change. The authors describe the genesis of recent financial innovations and how they have helped consumers in rich and poor countries alike by reducing costs, increasing accessibility, and improving convenience and efficiency. They connect the dots between early innovations in financial services and the wider revolution unfolding today. Changes may disrupt traditional financial services, especially banking, but they may also help us address major social challenges: opening new career paths for millennials, transforming government services, and expanding the gig economy in developed markets. Fintech could lead to economic infrastructure developments in rural areas and could facilitate emerging social security and healthcare systems in developing countries. The authors make this case with a rich combination of economic theory and case studies, including microanalyses of the effects of fintech innovations on individuals, as well as macroeconomic perspectives on fintech’s impact on societies. While celebrating fintech’s achievements to date, Laboure and Deffrennes also make recommendations for overcoming the obstacles that remain. The stakes—improved quality of life for all people—could not be higher.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConsolidation and merger of corporations. 0aEqualityxEconomic aspects. 0aFinancial institutionsxEffect of technological innovations on. 0aFinancial services industry. 0aInternational finance. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aDeffrennes, Nicolas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dD